She turned to a blank page and noted the date. Underneath, she wrote "11.5.648–13.12.648".
"Are you refreshing an old memory?" Ivory asked and looked at the old notebook. Kari nodded. "Do you think they'll let you out for Christmas? There are only a few days left."
Kari knocked twice on the lantern. "No," as Ivory had suspected. The Ice King never let Kari out, considering her a "blemish". She was born deaf and was the only daughter of the family, her siblings all being boys.
Similar things happened to Ivory as well. When Ivory came out as non-binary, it seemed as though the world was changing. As a punishment for this nonconformity, Ivory was given tasks where they spent most of their time alone.
Besides, Ivory was also forced to serve the Princess. It didn't bother Ivory much, though, since Ivory also gained a friend.
"You're going to have a birthday soon, aren't you?" Ivory asked, thinking that the Princess was having a birthday in a few days. Kari nodded with a sorrowful flicker in her bright blue eyes.
"Do you want to celebrate your birthday?" Ivory asked and thought back to the last time the Princess had answered this question.
"No," Kari knocked. Ivory knew that this was a difficult topic for her. Her birthday was the day she was locked in this room and her mother was banished. Ivory had been a baby at the time, but remembered how upset the staff and the residents of the city were. Ivory had heard that Eirwen was a popular queen. And that she somehow also could predict things that would actually come to pass.
"Now, what do you want to do?" Ivory asked. Kari looked up at Ivory excitedly. She held a piece of paper in her hand. On it was:
15 x 15 cm canvas
White, various blue hues.
Brushes in six different sizes
Easel
"Are you going to ask me to get you things?" Ivory turned to the silent Princess, whose braids swung back and forth with her vigorous knocking. "Yes?" Ivory chuckled softly. The otherwise closed-off Princess showed so much enthusiasm. It was the first time she asked for something that had nothing to do with books and came from outside her room.
"Okay! See you later?" Ivory asked, stood up and wove her way through the chaos of paper and notebooks.
Kari nodded, turned back to her notes and wrapped herself in her bedcovers.
Ivory left the room, relieved that the Princess finally ventured out of her comfort zone and asked for things beyond her reach, like paints.
Ivory walked back through the corridors and tried to ignore the whispers of the maids.
"I've heard that she's possessed by Queen Eirwen and that's why she keeps going back to this room."
"I've heard that she eats children in this room."
"She looks like a man, that's not normal, is it?"
Ivory covered her ears because she couldn't ignore the gossip, and continued on. The painter's studio was located in the east wing, behind the second door on the left.
Ivory approached the door, which was just as intricately decorated as Kari's door. On it was the White Dragon, one of the six primordial dragons that allegedly created Frostfell. For a history-obsessed painter, the White Dragon on the door made perfect sense.
Ivory opened the door, expecting the usual chaos. Splatters of paint everywhere, brushes and paper scattered all over the room, easels covering every inch of the wall. However, an unexpected scene unfolded instead. The entire room was spotless, and in front of a backdrop of red velvet stood a chair. Sitting on the chair was Crown Prince Aquilo, being painted.
"Good morning, Ivory! Would you like to watch how your future king is being painted?", asked Aquilo, winking at Ivory.
"Excuse me, little prince," Ivory said, largely ignoring him and gathering the things the quiet Princess had requested. "I'm only here to get painting supplies."
"Is my little girl already ready to leave?", asked Aquilo. "But I want you to stay!"
"I'm not, though." Ivory found the painting supplies on the list and put them in a box. "Also, I'm not a girl."
"Oh, sweetie, that's just a phase! As you grow older, you'll outgrow it," said he indistinctly.
"I must leave," said Ivory, feeling uneasy about the little prince's response. All the hurtful comments he and others had made about Ivory's gender identity in the past came flooding back. I just want to get out of here.
"Are you already going?" Suddenly the little prince appeared at the door, ignoring the painter's loud objections.
"That's not the behavior of a future king!" said Ivory.
"I don't think anyone will find out. People won't believe you and the painter will keep quiet if his life is worth anything." He glanced briefly at the painter and then leaned in closer to Ivory. "How about a date?" Ivory had been harassed before, but never by a prince, and certainly not by the Crown Prince.
"Do you actually know what the word 'No' means?" Ivory spat out, pushing the Crown Prince away.
"No," replied Aquilo with a smile. Of course, the Crown Prince, who can have anything he wants, doesn't know what the word "No" means.
Ivory rolled her eyes. "Why on earth would you want to go out with someone like me? You must have at least a hundred admirers."
"Actually, it's 50," he interrupted Ivory, still smiling. He tossed his hair back, which whipped around in the cold air.
"Now understand it! Why me, of all people? I'm a threat to the palace."
"You're the most beautiful girl I've ever seen." Aquilo lifted Ivory's chin with his finger, forcing Ivory to look at him.
